[6] Diarrhea - Viet Nam (Ho Chi Minh City)
Date: Wed 23 Jul 2014
Source: Saigon Giai Phong Daily [edited]
http://www.saigon-gpdaily.com.vn/Hochiminhcity/2014/7/109993/


An outbreak of acute diarrhea in Ho Chi Minh City's [HCMC] Binh Chanh District has killed a 10-month-old infant. A total of 7 babies are infected with the disease in Le Minh Xuan Commune in Binh Chanh District, including the 10-month-old infant who died. The Department of Health in HCMC said the outbreak of acute diarrhea has appeared due to poor environmental sanitation and hygiene conditions.

Medical experts fretted as residents in the commune live in stagnant ponds. For years, residents go for open defecation and they breed fish with their excrement in a pond. They also use contaminated pond water for washing and bathing.

Truong Van Hanh, deputy chairman of People's Committee in Binh Chanh District, said that local residents live temporarily here as the commune is zoned for house planning area, however, it is suspended for years. The district authority has encouraged people to stop open defecations to eliminate disease over ponds but people don't follow the warning; accordingly it is heavily contaminated, and water-related diseases breaks out.

Moreover, water supplier Le Minh Xuan is far from the area; consequently, the price of water increases many times. Many low-income people resort to using contaminated water for washing and bathing; hence, outbreaks of disease are unavoidable, and children are the 1st victims.

[Byline: Truong Ngoc]

